# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bethel-maine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bethel-maine/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:bethel-maine/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:bethel-maine/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:bethel-maine/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:bethel-maine/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:bethel-maine/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:bethel-maine/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:bethel-maine/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:bethel-maine/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bethel-maine/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:bethel-maine/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:bethel-maine/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:bethel-maine/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:bethel-maine/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:bethel-maine/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:bethel-maine/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:bethel-maine/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:bethel-maine/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:bethel-maine/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:bethel-maine/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:bethel-maine/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:bethel-maine/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:bethel-maine/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:bethel-maine/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:bethel-maine/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:bethel-maine/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:bethel-maine/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:bethel-maine/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bethel-maine/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] In 1853 the country contains 89 telegraph lines that stretched 23,261 miles (37,435 km).
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] When published in 1854, the country had an estimated 30,000 miles (48,000 km) of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:bethel-maine/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:bethel-maine/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] An Abenaki Indian village was once located on the north side of the Androscoggin River, but had been abandoned before its subsequent English settlement.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] In 1769, the township was granted as Sudbury-Canada by the Massachusetts General Court to Josiah Richardson of Sudbury, Massachusetts and others (or their heirs) for services at the Battle of Quebec in 1690.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] It was first settled in 1774 when Nathaniel Segar of Newton, Massachusetts started clearing the land.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The Revolutionary War, however, delayed many grantees from taking up their claims.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Only 10 families resided at Sudbury-Canada when it was plundered on August 3, 1781, during the last Indian attack in Maine.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Two inhabitants, Benjamin Clark and Nathaniel Segar, were abducted and held captive in Quebec until the war's conclusion, after which the community grew rapidly.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] In 1802, a trade road (now Route 26) was completed from Portland to Errol, New Hampshire, passing through Bethel and bringing growth.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Crops were planted on fertile intervales and meadows formerly cultivated by Indians.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Bethel became one of the best farming towns in the state, especially for hay and potatoes.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] In winter, farmers found work logging, with the lumber cut at sawmills operated by water power from streams.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Other manufacturers produced flour, leather and harnesses, furniture, boots and shoes, carriages, and marble and granite work.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The Bethel House, a large hotel, was built in 1833.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Lawrence Railroad opened to Bethel, carrying freight and summer tourists eager to escape the noise, heat and pollution of cities.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Between the Civil War and World War I, Bethel was a fashionable summer resort.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Several hotels were built facing the common or on Bethel Hill.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Begun in 1863, The Prospect Hotel was the largest, with a cupola from which guests could observe the mountains.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Tally-ho coaches provided tours through wilderness landscapes of the White Mountains and Maine.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Gehring's famed clinic for nervous disorders attracted many wealthy patients.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Between 1897 and 1926, a number of figures in the music world performed at the Maine Music Festivals organized by William Rogers Chapman.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] But with the advent of the automobile, tourists were no longer restricted by the limits of train service, but were free to explore.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Consequently, many big hotels built near the tracks lost patrons, declined and were eventually torn down.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The Prospect Hotel was largely destroyed by fire in 1911.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Although transportation patterns and preferences in vacation accommodations have changed, Bethel remains a tourist destination for its natural setting, history and recreation resources.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Beginning in 1947 Bethel became the site of "pioneering work" in organizational development.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Led by psychologist Kurt Lewin and, eventually, colleagues like Ken Benne and Ron Lippitt, research was conducted that helped lay the foundation for organizational development's theory and practice.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] T-groups and sensitivity training were refined to apply behavioral science to individual self-awareness and group functioning, in the service of organizational efficiency and productivity.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The National Training Laboratories (NTL) was organized by Lewin to lead this work, with much or it conducted during summer seasons at Gould Academy.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] These seasonal research and training sessions were well attended, attracting participants from across the country and around the world.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Increasingly, NTL became an important part of Bethel's economy, especially as the traditional wood product mill industries went into decline.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Although NTL moved its headquarters to Alexandria, Virginia in 2008, it continues to maintain a small summer legacy presence in Bethel.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Bethel is located on the western edge of the Oxford Hills and on the southern rim of the rugged Mahoosuc Range.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Nearby Locke and Barker Mountains lie within the Mahoosuc Range, which is a subrange of the White Mountains, a part of the Northern Appalachian Mountains.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Bethel and the surrounding area is drained by the Androscoggin River and its tributaries: the Alder, Pleasant and Sunday Rivers.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The north edge of Songo Pond lies within Bethel's boundary.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Just south of the boundary are located South Pond, North Pond and Bryant Ponds.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] According to the United States Census Bureau, the town has a total area of 65.91 square miles (170.71 km2), of which 64.60 square miles (167.31 km2) is land and 1.31 square miles (3.39 km2) is water.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] As of the census of 2010, there were 2,607 people, 1,121 households, and 707 families living in the town.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The population density was 40.4 inhabitants per square mile (15.6/km2).
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] There were 1,861 housing units at an average density of 28.8 per square mile (11.1/km2).
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The racial makeup of the town was 97.2% White, 0.5% African American, 0.2% Native American, 0.5% Asian, 0.5% from other races, and 1.0% from two or more races.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 1.2% of the population.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] There were 1,121 households, of which 29.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 47.6% were married couples living together, 9.5% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.9% had a male householder with no wife present, and 36.9% were non-families.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] 29.1% of all households were made up of individuals, and 13.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The average household size was 2.33 and the average family size was 2.83.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The median age in the town was 42.9 years.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] 23.3% of residents were under the age of 18; 6.1% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 23.6% were from 25 to 44; 31.1% were from 45 to 64; and 15.9% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The gender makeup of the town was 48.0% male and 52.0% female.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] As of the census of 2000, there were 2,411 people, 1,034 households, and 677 families living in the town.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The population density was 37.2 inhabitants per square mile (14.4/km2).
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] There were 1,448 housing units at an average density of 22.3 per square mile (8.6/km2).
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The racial makeup of the town was 98.09% White, 0.21% African American, 0.37% Native American, 0.50% Asian, 0.12% from other races, and 0.71% from two or more races.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 0.79% of the population.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] There were 1,034 households, out of which 27.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 52.5% were married couples living together, 9.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.5% were non-families.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] 26.9% of all households were made up of individuals, and 10.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The average household size was 2.33 and the average family size was 2.77.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] In the town, the population was spread out, with 22.4% under the age of 18, 6.8% from 18 to 24, 27.4% from 25 to 44, 27.6% from 45 to 64, and 15.8% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] For every 100 females, there were 96.0 males.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.6 males.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The median income for a household in the town was $33,803, and the median income for a family was $38,669.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] Males had a median income of $31,569 versus $18,859 for females.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] The per capita income for the town was $17,458.
[src:bethel-maine/bethel-maine] About 8.0% of families and 10.2% of the population were below the poverty line, including 11.2% of those under age 18 and 5.7% of those age 65 or over.
